04306nam a22007095i 9780814764206DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20022002nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147642067 a10.18574/nyu/9780814764206.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)548431  a(OCoLC)779828227  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aLAW0180002bisacsh04a347.73/262211 aMarcosson, Samuel A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOriginal Sin :bClarence Thomas and the Failure of the Constitutional Conservatives /cSamuel A. Marcosson. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2002] 4cÂ©2002  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCritical America ;v3300tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tChapter one. I Never Lie -- tChapter two. Multitudes in Me -- tChapter three. Hypothesis Testing -- tChapter four. States of Grace? -- tChapter five. The Smoking Gun -- tChapter six. A Bridge over Troubled Waters? -- tChapter seven. Any More Such Victories . . . -- tChapter eight. Legitimation -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOriginalism is the practice of reviewing constitutional cases by seeking to discern the framers' and ratifiers' intent. Original Sin argues that the "jurisprudence of original intent," represented on the current Supreme Court by Justices Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas, has failed on its own terms. Attempts to determine the framers' intent have not brought greater determinacy and legitimacy to the process of constitutional interpretation. Instead, the method has been marked by the very flaws-including self-interested reasoning and the manipulation of doctrine-that originalists argue marred the jurisprudence of the judicial "activists" of the Warren Court. Original Sin brings a rigorous review of the performance of the "new originalists" to the debate, applying their methodology to real cases. Marcosson focuses on the judicial decisions of Clarence Thomas, an avowed originalist who nevertheless advocates "color blind" readings of the Constitution which are at odds with the framers' ideas concerning anti-miscegenation and other laws. After critiquing what he sees as a troubling use of originalism and explaining why it has failed to provide a consistent basis for constitutional decision-making, the author goes on to offer an alternative approach: one that lends greater legitimacy to the Court's interpretations of the Constitution.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aConstitutional historyzUnited States. 7aLAW / Constitutional.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081475640940uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814764206.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814764206423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814764206/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK